  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "What is the pigeonhole principle? Give three non-trivial applications.",
  "response_text": "The Pigeonhole Principle is a fundamental concept in combinatorics and discrete mathematics. It states that if \\(n\\) items are put into \\(m\\) containers, with \\(n > m\\), then at least one container must contain more than one item. This principle can be applied to various problems to derive non-trivial conclusions.\n\n### Applications\n\n1. **Birthday Paradox**: In a group of 23 people, there is more than a 50% chance that two people share the same birthday. This application uses the pigeonhole principle to show that with only 23 people, it's highly likely that at least two individuals will have the same birthday. The \"pigeons\" are the people, and the \"pigeonholes\" are the days of the year.\n\n2. **Hash Collisions**: In computer science, hash functions map data of arbitrary size to fixed-size values. According to the pigeonhole principle, if more than \\(2^{32}\\) (or whatever the output size of the hash function is) pieces of data are hashed, then at least two pieces of data must hash to the same value. This is crucial for understanding why hash collisions occur and how they can affect the performance of hash tables.\n\n3. **Graph Theory**: In graph theory, the pigeonhole principle can be used to prove that in any graph with \\(n\\) vertices, if the sum of the degrees of all vertices is greater than \\(n(n-1)\\), then the graph must contain at least one triangle. Here, the \"pigeonholes\" represent the possible edges between vertices, and the \"pigeons\" are the actual edges present in the graph.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 6\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
